        Warning against China‚Äôs buildup</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
       Summary: The NATO Secretary General addressed China's military buildup over Taiwan and European security.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
       NATO Secretary General Mark Rutte has warned that China‚Äôs ‚Äúmassive‚Äù military buildup <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jun-25-spotlight-h2-4-raises-the-risk" target="_blank">raises the risk</a> of conflict over Taiwan. He suggested that a Chinese move on Taiwan could be accompanied by Russian aggression in Europe, thereby splitting NATO‚Äôs focus. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The Secretary General stated that China‚Äôs growing military power is a concern shared by NATO-aligned countries, including Japan, South Korea, and Australia. Rutte emphasized the need for increased defense spending and closer cooperation among allies. He pointed out that Chinese defense firms rank among the largest globally, showing China's ambition for power. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        NATO aims to increase defense spending to 5% of GDP and enhance military readiness. Rutte emphasized that unity and preparation are key to deterring threats and defending NATO territory effectively. However, rights groups are urging NATO leaders at the summit in The Hague to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jun-25-spotlight-h2-5-balance-defense-spending" target="_blank">balance defense spending</a> with human rights and international law.</p>
        
        </mj-text>
