     How did Slovenia become independent? 
 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/slovenia-early-recognition-croatia-baltics-georgia.jpg" alt="During the moratorium, independent Slovenia was recognized by Croatia, Lithuania, Georgia, Latvia, and Estonia" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>During the moratorium, independent Slovenia was recognized by Croatia, Lithuania, Georgia, Latvia, and Estonia. Credits: EPA/PETER NORTHALL</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Slovenia became independent on 25 June 1991. The idea of Slovenia was realized after World War I, when much of the Slovene-inhabited territory became part of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia. Following World War II, Slovenia gained some autonomy; however, by the 1980s, growing dissatisfaction and interethnic tensions fueled the voice for change. They advocated for democracy, a market economy, and independence.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The region <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jun-25-foundation-h1-13-broke-away" target="_blank">broke away</a> from Yugoslavia following a decisive referendum in December 1990. Over 88% of voters supported independence. This declaration led to a short <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-jun-25-foundation-h1-14-ten-day-war" target="_blank">ten-day war</a> with the Yugoslav People‚Äôs Army. After the war, Slovenia took control of its borders. Their distinct identity, which makes them closer to Central and Western Europe, was a significant reason for the rebellion.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         They were more economically advanced than the rest of Yugoslavia. Some of the motives were concern about how Yugoslavia evolved after Tito died in the 1980s, such as Serbia gaining more influence and power over Yugoslavia, and dissatisfaction with Slobodan Milo≈°eviƒá. Slovenia gained international recognition in early 1992.</p>
        </mj-text>
